{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"Let's talk trash."}]},{"cues":[{"time":2000,"text":"You know, we had to be taught"},{"time":5000,"text":"to renounce the powerful conservation ethic"},{"time":8000,"text":"we developed during the Great Depression and World War II."},{"time":11000,"text":"After the war, we needed to direct our enormous production capacity"},{"time":14000,"text":"toward creation of products for peacetime."},{"time":17000,"text":"Life Magazine helped in this effort"},{"time":20000,"text":"by announcing the introduction of throwaways"},{"time":23000,"text":"that would liberate the housewife from the drudgery of doing dishes."}]},{"cues":[{"time":26000,"text":"Mental note to the liberators:"},{"time":28000,"text":"throwaway plastics take a lot of space and don't biodegrade."},{"time":31000,"text":"Only we humans make waste that nature can't digest."}]},{"cues":[{"time":36000,"text":"Plastics are also hard to recycle."},{"time":39000,"text":"A teacher told me how to express the under-five-percent"},{"time":42000,"text":"of plastics recovered in our waste stream."},{"time":45000,"text":"It's diddly-point-squat."},{"time":48000,"text":"That's the percentage we recycle."}]},{"cues":[{"time":54000,"text":"Now, melting point has a lot to do with this."},{"time":57000,"text":"Plastic is not purified by the re-melting process like glass and metal."},{"time":60000,"text":"It begins to melt below the boiling point of water"},{"time":63000,"text":"and does not drive off the oily contaminants"},{"time":66000,"text":"for which it is a sponge."},{"time":69000,"text":"Half of each year's 100 billion pounds of thermal plastic pellets"},{"time":72000,"text":"will be made into fast-track trash."},{"time":75000,"text":"A large, unruly fraction of our trash"},{"time":78000,"text":"will flow downriver to the sea."}]},{"cues":[{"time":81000,"text":"Here is the accumulation at Biona Creek next to the L.A. airport."},{"time":84000,"text":"And here is the flotsam near California State University Long Beach"},{"time":89000,"text":"and the diesel plant we visited yesterday."}]},{"cues":[{"time":91000,"text":"In spite of deposit fees,"},{"time":93000,"text":"much of this trash leading out to the sea will be plastic beverage bottles."},{"time":96000,"text":"We use two million of them in the United States every five minutes,"},{"time":100000,"text":"here imaged by TED presenter Chris Jordan,"},{"time":103000,"text":"who artfully documents mass consumption and zooms in for more detail."}]},{"cues":[{"time":109000,"text":"Here is a remote island repository for bottles"},{"time":113000,"text":"off the coast of Baja California."},{"time":116000,"text":"Isla San Roque is an uninhabited bird rookery"},{"time":118000,"text":"off Baja's sparsely populated central coast."},{"time":120000,"text":"Notice that the bottles here have caps on them."},{"time":123000,"text":"Bottles made of polyethylene terephthalate, PET,"},{"time":127000,"text":"will sink in seawater and not make it this far from civilization."},{"time":130000,"text":"Also, the caps are produced in separate factories"},{"time":133000,"text":"from a different plastic, polypropylene."},{"time":136000,"text":"They will float in seawater,"},{"time":138000,"text":"but unfortunately do not get recycled under the bottle bills."}]},{"cues":[{"time":142000,"text":"Let's trace the journey of the millions of caps"},{"time":145000,"text":"that make it to sea solo."},{"time":147000,"text":"After a year the ones from Japan are heading straight across the Pacific,"},{"time":150000,"text":"while ours get caught in the California current"},{"time":153000,"text":"and first head down to the latitude of Cabo San Lucas."},{"time":156000,"text":"After ten years, a lot of the Japanese caps"},{"time":159000,"text":"are in what we call the Eastern Garbage Patch,"},{"time":161000,"text":"while ours litter the Philippines."},{"time":163000,"text":"After 20 years, we see emerging the debris accumulation zone"},{"time":166000,"text":"of the North Pacific Gyre."}]},{"cues":[{"time":169000,"text":"It so happens that millions of albatross"},{"time":171000,"text":"nesting on Kure and Midway atolls"},{"time":173000,"text":"in the Northwest Hawaiian Islands National Monument"},{"time":176000,"text":"forage here and scavenge whatever they can find"},{"time":179000,"text":"for regurgitation to their chicks."},{"time":181000,"text":"A four-month old Laysan Albatross chick"},{"time":184000,"text":"died with this in its stomach."},{"time":187000,"text":"Hundreds of thousands of the goose-sized chicks are dying"},{"time":192000,"text":"with stomachs full of bottle caps and other rubbish,"},{"time":195000,"text":"like cigarette lighters ..."},{"time":198000,"text":"but, mostly bottle caps."},{"time":201000,"text":"Sadly, their parents mistake bottle caps for food"},{"time":204000,"text":"tossing about in the ocean surface."}]},{"cues":[{"time":207000,"text":"The retainer rings for the caps"},{"time":209000,"text":"also have consequences for aquatic animals."},{"time":212000,"text":"This is Mae West,"},{"time":214000,"text":"still alive at a zookeeper's home in New Orleans."}]},{"cues":[{"time":217000,"text":"I wanted to see what my home town of Long Beach was contributing to the problem,"},{"time":221000,"text":"so on Coastal Clean-Up Day in 2005"},{"time":224000,"text":"I went to the Long Beach Peninsula, at the east end of our long beach."},{"time":227000,"text":"We cleaned up the swaths of beach shown."},{"time":230000,"text":"I offered five cents each for bottle caps."},{"time":233000,"text":"I got plenty of takers."},{"time":235000,"text":"Here are the 1,100 bottle caps they collected."},{"time":238000,"text":"I thought I would spend 20 bucks."},{"time":241000,"text":"That day I ended up spending nearly 60."}]},{"cues":[{"time":244000,"text":"I separated them by color"},{"time":246000,"text":"and put them on display the next Earth Day"},{"time":248000,"text":"at Cabrillo Marine Aquarium in San Pedro."},{"time":250000,"text":"Governor Schwarzenegger and his wife Maria stopped by to discuss the display."},{"time":254000,"text":"In spite of my \"girly man\" hat, crocheted from plastic shopping bags,"},{"time":257000,"text":"they shook my hand. (Laughter)"},{"time":261000,"text":"I showed him and Maria a zooplankton trawl"},{"time":264000,"text":"from the gyre north of Hawaii"},{"time":267000,"text":"with more plastic than plankton."}]},{"cues":[{"time":269000,"text":"Here's what our trawl samples from the plastic soup our ocean has become look like."},{"time":274000,"text":"Trawling a zooplankton net on the surface for a mile"},{"time":277000,"text":"produces samples like this."},{"time":280000,"text":"And this."},{"time":283000,"text":"Now, when the debris washes up on the beaches of Hawaii"},{"time":286000,"text":"it looks like this."},{"time":288000,"text":"And this particular beach is Kailua Beach,"},{"time":290000,"text":"the beach where our president and his family vacationed before moving to Washington."}]},{"cues":[{"time":293000,"text":"Now, how do we analyze samples like this one"},{"time":296000,"text":"that contain more plastic than plankton?"},{"time":299000,"text":"We sort the plastic fragments into different size classes,"},{"time":302000,"text":"from five millimeters to one-third of a millimeter."},{"time":305000,"text":"Small bits of plastic concentrate persistent organic pollutants"},{"time":309000,"text":"up to a million times their levels in the surrounding seawater."}]},{"cues":[{"time":313000,"text":"We wanted to see if the most common fish in the deep ocean,"},{"time":316000,"text":"at the base of the food chain,"},{"time":318000,"text":"was ingesting these poison pills."},{"time":320000,"text":"We did hundreds of necropsies,"},{"time":323000,"text":"and over a third had polluted plastic fragments in their stomachs."},{"time":326000,"text":"The record-holder, only two-and-a-half inches long,"},{"time":329000,"text":"had 84 pieces in its tiny stomach."}]},{"cues":[{"time":332000,"text":"Now, you can buy certified organic produce."},{"time":335000,"text":"But no fishmonger on Earth"},{"time":338000,"text":"can sell you a certified organic wild-caught fish."}]},{"cues":[{"time":343000,"text":"This is the legacy we are leaving to future generations."},{"time":348000,"text":"The throwaway society cannot be contained --"},{"time":351000,"text":"it has gone global."},{"time":354000,"text":"We simply cannot store and maintain or recycle all our stuff."},{"time":357000,"text":"We have to throw it away."},{"time":359000,"text":"Now, the market can do a lot for us,"},{"time":362000,"text":"but it can't fix the natural system in the ocean we've broken."},{"time":365000,"text":"All the king's horses and all the king's men ..."},{"time":368000,"text":"will never gather up all the plastic and put the ocean back together again."}]},{"cues":[{"time":374000,"text":"Narrator (Video): The levels are increasing,"},{"time":376000,"text":"the amount of packaging is increasing,"},{"time":378000,"text":"the \"throwaway\" concept of living is proliferating,"},{"time":381000,"text":"and it's showing up in the ocean."}]},{"cues":[{"time":384000,"text":"Anchor: He offers no hope of cleaning it up."},{"time":387000,"text":"Straining the ocean for plastic"},{"time":390000,"text":"would be beyond the budget of any country"},{"time":393000,"text":"and it might kill untold amounts of sea life in the process."},{"time":396000,"text":"The solution, Moore says, is to stop the plastic at its source:"},{"time":399000,"text":"stop it on land before it falls in the ocean."},{"time":406000,"text":"And in a plastic-wrapped and packaged world,"},{"time":409000,"text":"he doesn't hold out much hope for that, either."},{"time":412000,"text":"This is Brian Rooney for Nightline,"},{"time":414000,"text":"in Long Beach, California."}]},{"cues":[{"time":420000,"text":"Charles Moore: Thank you."}]}]}